Bangalore,The Organic World - Indiranagar,"12th Main, 7th Cross Rd, 7th Cross, HAL 2nd Stage, Indiranagar, Bengaluru, Karnataka 560008","https://www.google.com/maps/place/The+Organic+World+-+Indiranagar/@12.9704614,77.6450913,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m6!3m5!1s0x3bae172ac41b5819:0x11bcd2e9e87bcdc6!8m2!3d12.9704614!4d77.6450913!16s%2Fg%2F11frdzkd5r",4.4,0,Ayt,3.0,3 years ago,0,"Response from the owner 3 years ago Dear Aayati Sengupta, Thank you for your feedback. We understand and appreciate your concern. One of the most common queries and feedback we receive from our valued customers is related to the price of organic products. To explain, the average premium is 1.30x for organic products in general (and not only in The Organic World) as compared to non-organic products. This has to do with the quality of inputs required for high-quality organic produce right from the quality of ingredients involved to processes etc involved in the manufacturing of those products. This premium is coming down based on more players entering production + retailing with things becoming more organised. However, at The Organic World, we constantly look for how we can offer our customers best price options to make the switch to chemical-free living both accessible and affordable. One of the biggest factors in play here are fruits and vegetables and our organic fruits and vegetables are among the lowest priced in the city, as compared to other organic fruits and vegetable brands. When it comes groceries such as flour, grains, pulses and dairy, we are consistently working with our partner brands as well as farms to look at how we can help reduce the input cost and thereby pass on the benefits to our customers. We do hope this answers your query and we look forward to having you shop with us in the future again. Thank you, The Organic World team","They have a lot of stuff that's organically sourced, according to the advertising. There's also a small eatery inside which I didn't try. Even though the place is fairly well stocked, it's incredibly expensive according to me. That in itself wouldn't be a problem since a place can be expensive but they have a banner outside the shop that reads ""Organic and affordable"". That felt like false advertising to me. They mostly store companies that have high priced products. I bought some spiced paneer, a jar of ghee and a couple of chocolates and incense. Apart from the incense which are from Auroville, everything was expensive. The paneer (around 200-220 gm) was around 250 rupees, the chocolates about the same and the ghee around 550 bucks. Incense was around 30 or 35. Service staff are nice.",2026-05-11 17:24:19
